Table 11. Specifically 
we look into the statistics of our track length, pedestrian 
velocities, bounding box ratio, occlusions and class distri-
bution. Average pedestrian velocity is the mean distance 
travelled by the tracks between each frame in pixels, aver-
aged over the whole sequence and represented as px.s ?1 . 
Bounding box ratio (BBR) denotes the ratio of spatial di-
mensions of frames to that of average bounding box in the 
respective sequence. Occlusion refers to the average time 
(in frames) that a target was annotated with a visibility flag 
of "0". 
We compare CroHD with multiple pedestrian tracking 
benchmarks based on number of pedestrian annotations, 
pedestrian densities and tracks annotated as depicted in Ta-
ble 6. The density in the table refers to the average num-
ber of pedestrian annotations per frame. CroHD has the 
largest pedestrian annotation, pedestrian density and num-
ber of tracks.
